you were going to the game,
other than the two defendants?

02:11:01.752 --> 02:11:04.016
I don't think so.

02:11:04.088 --> 02:11:06.989
- Was anyone with you
when you purchased the tickets?
- No.

02:11:07.057 --> 02:11:10.220
- No one saw you buy the tickets?
- That's right.

02:11:10.294 --> 02:11:12.455
- Did you get a receipt?
- No, I didn't.

02:11:12.529 --> 02:11:16.795
- Pay by check, MasterCard, Visa?
- No. I paid by cash.

02:11:16.867 --> 02:11:19.233
I usually pay for things in cash.

02:11:21.004 --> 02:11:23.529
You care for the boys in your parish,
don't you, Father?

02:11:23.607 --> 02:11:25.802
Very much.

02:11:25.876 --> 02:11:29.107
And there isn't anything you
wouldn't do for them. Am I right?

02:11:29.179 --> 02:11:31.647
Anything in my power to do,
I would make it a point.

02:11:32.549 --> 02:11:35.848
You're like a father, a good father,
looking out for one of his sons.

02:11:36.754 --> 02:11:40.190
- Something along those lines, yes.
- And is it true, then...

02:11:40.257 --> 02:11:43.249
as a good father, you would want
to protect them from something
they shouldn't have done?

02:11:43.327 --> 02:11:47.730
As much as I would want to protect them
from something someone
else said they did, yes.

02:11:47.798 --> 02:11:51.393
- Like a murder?
- Yes, like a murder.

02:11:52.736 --> 02:11:54.704
Let me get this straight then.

02:11:54.772 --> 02:11:57.707
No one knew you were going to the game.
No one saw you at the game.

02:11:57.775 --> 02:12:00.903
No one saw you buy tickets for the game.
There's no record
you even bought tickets.

02:12:00.978 --> 02:12:04.175
You have no receipt for the tickets.
Am I correct?

02:12:05.749 --> 02:12:09.617
- Yes, that's correct.
- Then how do we really know, Father?

02:12:09.686 --> 02:12:12.120
How do we know
you and the two defendants...

02:12:12.189 --> 02:12:15.181
were at the game
on the night of the murder?

02:12:15.259 --> 02:12:18.695
I'm telling you as a witness
and as a priest we were at the game.

02:12:18.762 --> 02:12:22.755
Yes, as a priest.
And a priest wouldn't lie. Am I right?

02:12:22.833 --> 02:12:26.860
A priest with ticket stubs
wouldn't need to lie...

02:12:26.937 --> 02:12:31.067
and I always keep the stubs.

02:12:35.045 --> 02:12:38.014
Do you want to see them?

02:12:42.252 --> 02:12:46.188
Uh, why is that, Father?
Why... Uh, why do you keep the stubs?

02:12:46.256 --> 02:12:50.124
Because you never know when someone
might want more than your word.

02:12:51.461 --> 02:12:53.952
Has anyone ever questioned
your word before today?

02:12:54.031 --> 02:12:58.491
No. No one ever has.
But there's a first time for everything.

02:13:08.178 --> 02:13:11.272
I have no further questions.
Thank you, Father.

02:13:13.050 --> 02:13:15.450
Thank you, Father.
You may step down.

02:13:22.759 --> 02:13:25.319
I've never recovered from seeing
Father Bobby take the stand...

02:13:25.395 --> 02:13:29.695
and lie for us to even
the score forJohn and Tommy.

02:13:29.766 --> 02:13:33.725
He didn't just testify for them.
He testified against Wilkinson...

02:13:33.804 --> 02:13:36.568
and the evil that had lived there
for too long.

02:13:36.640 --> 02:13:39.040
Still, I was sorry he had to do it.

02:13:45.849 --> 02:13:48.477
With respect to the charge
of murder in the second degree...

02:13:48.552 --> 02:13:52.613
do you find the defendant,
John Reilly, guilt or not guilty?

02:13:52.689 --> 02:13:56.386
- Not guilty.
- With respect to the charge
of murder in the second degree...

02:13:56.460 --> 02:13:59.623
do you find the defendant,
Thomas Marcano...

02:13:59.696 --> 02:14:02.893
- Guilty or not guilty?
- Not guilty.

02:14:02.966 --> 02:14:06.834
Thank you very much.
This jury is discharged.

02:14:27.491 --> 02:14:29.857
Hi. How are you?
Could I get a hot dog?

02:14:29.927 --> 02:14:32.919
- Yeah.
- Uh, mustard, relish.

02:14:33.931 --> 02:14:35.922
A lot of relish.

02:14:38.068 --> 02:14:40.434
Give him two napkins.

02:14:45.242 --> 02:14:48.006
You did good in there, Counselor.

02:14:49.279 --> 02:14:51.543
So, what happens to you now?

02:14:51.615 --> 02:14:54.550
What happens? I walk away.

02:14:54.618 --> 02:14:58.019
I'll wait a few weeks,
I'll hand in my notice...

02:14:58.088 --> 02:15:00.648
and after the way
I handled this case...

02:15:00.724 --> 02:15:03.420
they won't be in a rush
to keep me from the door.

02:15:05.228 --> 02:15:08.561
So you switch to the other side
and work as a defense lawyer.

02:15:08.632 --> 02:15:10.566
The money's better.

02:15:10.634 --> 02:15:14.195
There's always gonna be more bad guys
than good, Mikey.

02:15:15.072 --> 02:15:17.870
And can you imagine the work
you'd get from John and Tommy's crew?

02:15:17.941 --> 02:15:20.466
- Yeah.
- That's a house and a pool.

02:15:22.446 --> 02:15:24.914
Not for me.

02:15:24.982 --> 02:15:28.042
I've seen all the law
I want to see.

02:15:28.118 --> 02:15:31.554
- It's time for something else.
- Like what?

02:15:31.621 --> 02:15:34.215
Let you know when I know.

02:15:34.291 --> 02:15:36.521
You know, you're too old
to play for the Yankees...

02:15:36.593 --> 02:15:38.527
and you're too young
to take up golf.

02:15:38.595 --> 02:15:42.827
Why you shooting holes
through all my plans? You're...
You're gonna make me panic.

02:15:42.899 --> 02:15:46.960
You'll work it out.
You always have.

02:15:50.507 --> 02:15:53.101
It's time for quiet, Shakes.

02:15:54.478 --> 02:15:58.437
I just want to shut my eyes and
not have to see the places I've been.

02:16:00.550 --> 02:16:02.415
I'm weary.

02:16:05.789 --> 02:16:07.723
I don't know.

02:16:10.093 --> 02:16:13.824
Maybe I'll get lucky,
forget I was even there.

02:16:13.897 --> 02:16:19.301
Well, don't disappear on me, Counselor.
I may need a good lawyer one day.

02:16:19.369 --> 02:16:22.304
- Hey, you can't afford a good lawyer.
- Okay.

02:16:24.041 --> 02:16:28.341
I may need a good friend though.

02:16:28.412 --> 02:16:31.279
I'll find you when you do.
Count on it.

02:16:33.183 --> 02:16:35.174
Always have.

02:16:40.790 --> 02:16:42.918
A full month had passed
since the acquittal...

02:16:42.993 --> 02:16:44.927
and no one had made contact.

02:16:44.995 --> 02:16:46.963
In those few weeks,
our lives had reverted back...

02:16:47.030 --> 02:16:50.261
to what they'd been
prior to the murder of Sean Nokes.

02:16:50.333 --> 02:16:53.530
Carol had returned to her stack
of social service files...

02:16:53.602 --> 02:16:56.197
helping troubled teens
and single mothers.

02:16:56.272 --> 02:16:58.537
John and Tommy
went back to the streets...

02:16:58.608 --> 02:17:00.666
running the West Side Boys.

02:17:00.744 --> 02:17:03.508
I was promoted from clerk
to reporter trainee...

02:17:03.580 --> 02:17:05.605
covering the entertainment beat.

02:17:05.682 --> 02:17:07.946
Michael, as he had promised,
resigned from his job...

02:17:08.018 --> 02:17:11.044
after working the losing end
of a "can't miss" case.

02:17:11.120 --> 02:17:13.055
Excuse me.

02:17:15.125 --> 02:17:18.218
I don't know
how to fuckin' thank you.

02:17:19.963 --> 02:17:22.830
- All right.
- I can't believe what you did.

02:17:22.898 --> 02:17:26.096
- I can't believe you got away with it.
- It wasn't me, man. That was Mikey.

02:17:26.169 --> 02:17:29.002
- It was all Mikey's plan.
- You know, when I first heard
he was taking the case...

02:17:29.072 --> 02:17:31.302
- I was gonna have him burned.
- And?

02:17:31.374 --> 02:17:34.275
And I figured he's a friend,
and if you gotta be sent away
on a murder rap, who better to do it?

02:17:34.343 --> 02:17:37.313
Well, the way he's handling
his end of the case, I thought
he sucked as a lawyer.

02:17:37.379 --> 02:17:39.848
- I started feeling sorry
for the bastard.
- Hey.

02:17:39.915 --> 02:17:42.646
Never feel sorry for a lawyer.

02:17:42.718 --> 02:17:45.347
Get over here, Counselor!

02:17:45.422 --> 02:17:47.913
You are the real count...

02:17:47.991 --> 02:17:51.790
alive and well
and living in New York City.

02:17:51.861 --> 02:17:55.161
- Fuckin' maniac.
- All right. All right.

02:17:55.232 --> 02:17:58.360
- You maniac. Jesus!
- What is this, a gay bar?

02:17:59.102 --> 02:18:01.536
- Uh-oh.
- It was until you came in.

02:18:01.605 --> 02:18:04.972
Why don't you give me a kiss
to go with that hello?

02:18:09.612 --> 02:18:12.343
- Get out of the way.
- You're next.

02:18:15.418 --> 02:18:18.683
- Break it up there!
- Let's have a drink.

02:18:23.793 --> 02:18:27.193
- The Four Gladiators.
- Oh, he's right. I forget, you know?

02:18:27.263 --> 02:18:30.960
The Four Gladiators. Worst quartet
to ever hold a Hell's Kitchen corner,
swear to God.

02:18:31.034 --> 02:18:34.128
- Yeah, but what was that name
that Shakes wanted to call it?
- No, no, no, no.

02:18:34.204 --> 02:18:36.798
Genius wanted to call it
the Count and his Cristos.

02:18:36.873 --> 02:18:40.775
- Nice name!
- It's so sweet, isn't it?

02:18:40.843 --> 02:18:43.074
- That would've sent albums
flying out of the stores.
- We weren't that...

02:18:43.146 --> 02:18:45.671
We weren't that bad. I mean,
some people wanted to hear us sing.

02:18:45.749 --> 02:18:48.912
- We were that bad.
- Yeah, the kids at the deaf
school don't count.

02:18:52.455 --> 02:18:54.787
- One song for Carol.
- Oh, no.

02:18:54.858 --> 02:18:57.451
- I retired a long time ago.
- Come on, you mutts.
- Wait, wait, wait.

02:18:57.527 --> 02:19:01.361
Don't you guys have to go
and shoot somebody?

02:19:01.431 --> 02:19:03.193
- Ohh!
- No!

02:19:04.567 --> 02:19:08.094
No. We always got time
for a song.

02:19:08.171 --> 02:19:10.537
Just kidding.
You know what I'm saying?

02:19:10.607 --> 02:19:13.166
- Wine, anybody?
- You pick it, but nothin' too slow.

02:19:13.243 --> 02:19:15.609
All right. Start us off.

02:19:18.013 --> 02:19:21.677
- How many songs do you know?
- One.

02:19:26.121 --> 02:19:32.357
<i>Walk like a man</i>

02:19:33.830 --> 02:19:37.891
<i>Walk like a man, fast as you can</i>

02:19:37.968 --> 02:19:41.904
<i>Walk like a man, my son</i>

02:19:41.972 --> 02:19:45.532
<i>I'll tell the world</i>
<i>to forget about the girl</i>

02:20:01.925 --> 02:20:05.691
On March 16, 1984,
John Reilly's wilted body...

02:20:05.762 --> 02:20:08.060
was found face up
in a tenement building...

02:20:08.131 --> 02:20:10.998
right next to the bottle
of boiler gin that killed him.

02:20:11.067 --> 02:20:15.128
At the time of his death, he was
a suspect in five unsolved homicides.

02:20:15.205 --> 02:20:17.935
He was two weeks past
his 29th birthday.

02:20:22.212 --> 02:20:26.342
Thomas Marcano died
on July 26, 1985.

02:20:26.416 --> 02:20:28.907
He was shot at close range
five times.

02:20:28.985 --> 02:20:31.579
The body lay undiscovered
for more than a week.

02:20:31.655 --> 02:20:35.182
There was a crucifix and a picture
of St. Jude in his picket.

02:20:35.258 --> 02:20:37.249
He was 29 years old.

02:20:38.962 --> 02:20:42.295
Michael Sullivan lives in a small
town in the English countryside...

02:20:42.365 --> 02:20:44.833
where he works part-time
as a carpenter.

02:20:44.901 --> 02:20:48.132
He no longer practices law,
and he has never married.

02:20:48.204 --> 02:20:50.468
He lives quietly and alone.

02:20:52.742 --> 02:20:55.836
Carol still works
for a social service agency...

02:20:55.912 --> 02:20:57.379
and lives in Hell's Kitchen.

02:20:57.447 --> 02:20:58.539
She has never married...

02:20:58.615 --> 02:21:02.574
but is a single mother
supporting a growing 12-year-old son.

02:21:02.652 --> 02:21:06.110
The boy,
John Thomas Michael Martinez...

02:21:06.189 --> 02:21:09.750
Ioves to read and is called
"Shakes" by his mother.

02:21:11.961 --> 02:21:16.091
It was our special night,
and we held it for as long as we could.

02:21:16.166 --> 02:21:18.464
It was our happy ending...

02:21:18.535 --> 02:21:21.595
and the last time we would ever
be together again.

02:22:10.587 --> 02:22:12.919
The future lay sparkling ahead...

02:22:12.989 --> 02:22:16.117
and we thought we would
know each other forever.

